OBMC prefers calling out the explicit type if it's not obvious what is being returned.
This format is more conventional C++, and should avoid a copy operation.

suggestion:
Take advantage of C++ containers, and move mechanics.
Skeleton example:
std::string ncsiBCDToStr(const std::vector<uint8_t>& raw)
{
    std::string bcd{};
    for (const auto it : raw)
    {
        bcd.push_back(it);
    }
    // calculate correction for last element
    bcd.at(last_idx) = correction;
    return bcd;
}

You can iterate over the vector without having to manually deal with bounds checking.
You can build the version string piece by piece without having to manually calculate the last char. You just add your last calculation to the end.
Lastly, because 'bcd' is a local string, and you are returning that local string, C++ will use move mechanics to transfer the scope of the string to the caller.
Look for ways to avoid using raw C pointers.

Following the suggestion above you can replace this with:
    std::vector<uint8_t> foo(
        getVersnIdResp->versnIdData.ncsiVersion,
        getVersnIdResp->versnIdData.firmwareName - 1);
    lg2::debug("your message....", ....., ncsiBCDToStr(foo));
